# nl-rag distilled facts — domain: ddos-mitigation-deep
# one declarative sentence per line; load with:  neuron --db app.db import pack.facts --scope knowledge
[src:ddos-mitigation-deep/anycast] The first documented use of anycast routing for topological load-balancing of Internet-connected services was in 1989; the technique was first formally documented in the IETF four years later.
[src:ddos-mitigation-deep/anycast] It was first applied to critical infrastructure in 2001 with the anycasting of the I-root nameserver.
[src:ddos-mitigation-deep/anycast] Early objections to the deployment of anycast routing centered on the perceived conflict between long-lived TCP connections and the volatility of the Internet's routed topology.
[src:ddos-mitigation-deep/anycast] In practice, such problems were not observed, and these objections dissipated by the early 2000s.
[src:ddos-mitigation-deep/anycast] Many initial anycast deployments consisted of DNS servers, using principally UDP transport.
[src:ddos-mitigation-deep/anycast] Measurements of long-term anycast flows revealed very few failures due to mid-connection instance switches, far fewer (less than 0.017% or "less than one flow per ten thousand per hour of duration" according to various sources) than were attributed to other causes of failure.
[src:ddos-mitigation-deep/anycast] Numerous mechanisms were developed to efficiently share state between anycast instances.
[src:ddos-mitigation-deep/anycast] And some TCP-based protocols, notably HTTP, incorporated "redirect" mechanisms, whereby anycast service addresses could be used to locate the nearest instance of a service, whereupon a user would be redirected to that specific instance prior to the initiation of any long-lived stateful transaction.
[src:ddos-mitigation-deep/anycast] Anycast is implemented in the Internet via Border Gateway Protocol (BGP), where multiple hosts (usually in different geographic areas) are given the same anycast IP address and they all announce it to their BGP table.
[src:ddos-mitigation-deep/anycast] Routers consider these to be alternative routes to the same destination, even though they are actually routes to different destinations with the same address.
[src:ddos-mitigation-deep/anycast] Routers will often select the path with fewer hops, which leads to the one closer to the client as being selected (often faster).
[src:ddos-mitigation-deep/anycast] It doesn't always happen, as some routers will choose other metrics (least congested, cheapest).
[src:ddos-mitigation-deep/anycast] Anycast is supported explicitly in the IPv6 addressing architecture.
[src:ddos-mitigation-deep/anycast] The lowest address within an IPv6 subnet (interface identifier 0) is reserved as the "Subnet Router" anycast address.
[src:ddos-mitigation-deep/anycast] In addition, the highest 128 interface identifiers within a subnet are also reserved as anycast addresses.
[src:ddos-mitigation-deep/anycast] The method used in IPv4 of advertising multiple routes in BGP to multiply-assigned unicast addresses also still works in IPv6, and can be used to route packets to the nearest of several geographically dispersed hosts with the same address.
[src:ddos-mitigation-deep/anycast] This approach, which does not depend on anycast-aware routers, has the same use cases together with the same problems and limitations as in IPv4.
[src:ddos-mitigation-deep/anycast] With the growth of the Internet, network services increasingly have high-availability requirements.
[src:ddos-mitigation-deep/anycast] As a result, operation of anycast services has grown in popularity among network operators.
[src:ddos-mitigation-deep/anycast] All Internet root nameservers are implemented as clusters of hosts using anycast addressing.
[src:ddos-mitigation-deep/anycast] All 13 root servers A–M exist in multiple locations, with 11 on multiple continents.
[src:ddos-mitigation-deep/anycast] (Root servers B and H exist in two U.S. locations.) The servers use anycast address announcements to provide a decentralized service.
[src:ddos-mitigation-deep/anycast] This has accelerated the deployment of physical (rather than logical) root servers outside the United States.
[src:ddos-mitigation-deep/anycast] Many commercial DNS providers have switched to an IP anycast environment to increase query performance and redundancy, and to implement load balancing.
[src:ddos-mitigation-deep/anycast] In IPv4 to IPv6 transitioning, anycast addressing may be deployed to provide IPv6 compatibility to IPv4 hosts.
[src:ddos-mitigation-deep/anycast] This method, 6to4, uses a default gateway with the IP address *192.88.99.1*.
[src:ddos-mitigation-deep/anycast] This allows multiple providers to implement 6to4 gateways without hosts having to know each individual provider's gateway addresses.
[src:ddos-mitigation-deep/anycast] 6to4 has been deprecated in response to native IPv6 becoming more prevalent.
[src:ddos-mitigation-deep/anycast] Content delivery networks may use anycast for actual HTTP connections to their distribution centers, or for DNS.
[src:ddos-mitigation-deep/anycast] Because most HTTP connections to such networks request static content such as images and style sheets, they are generally short-lived and stateless across subsequent TCP sessions.
[src:ddos-mitigation-deep/anycast] The general stability of routes and statelessness of connections makes anycast suitable for this application, even though it uses TCP.
[src:ddos-mitigation-deep/anycast] Anycast rendezvous point can be used in Multicast Source Discovery Protocol (MSDP) and its advantageous application as Anycast RP is an intra-domain feature that provides redundancy and load-sharing capabilities.
[src:ddos-mitigation-deep/anycast] If the multiple anycast rendezvous point is used, IP routing automatically will select the topologically closest rendezvous point for each source and receiver.
[src:ddos-mitigation-deep/anycast] It would provide a multicast network with the fault tolerance requirements.
[src:ddos-mitigation-deep/anycast] Anycast allows any operator whose routing information is accepted by an intermediate router to hijack any packets intended for the anycast address.
[src:ddos-mitigation-deep/anycast] While this at first sight appears insecure, it is no different from the routing of ordinary IP packets, and no more or less secure.
[src:ddos-mitigation-deep/anycast] As with conventional IP routing, careful filtering of who is and is not allowed to propagate route announcements is crucial to prevent man-in-the-middle or blackhole attacks.
[src:ddos-mitigation-deep/anycast] The former can also be prevented by encrypting and authenticating messages, such as using Transport Layer Security, while the latter can be frustrated by onion routing.
[src:ddos-mitigation-deep/anycast] Anycast is normally highly reliable, as it can provide automatic failover without adding complexity or new potential points of failure.
[src:ddos-mitigation-deep/anycast] Anycast applications typically feature external "heartbeat" monitoring of the server's function, and withdraw the route announcement if the server fails.
[src:ddos-mitigation-deep/anycast] In some cases this is done by the actual servers announcing the anycast prefix to the router over OSPF or another IGP.
[src:ddos-mitigation-deep/anycast] If the servers die, the router will automatically withdraw the announcement.
[src:ddos-mitigation-deep/anycast] "Heartbeat" functionality is important because, if the announcement continues for a failed server, the server will act as a "black hole" for nearby clients; this is the most serious mode of failure for an anycast system.
[src:ddos-mitigation-deep/anycast] Even in this event, this kind of failure will only cause a total failure for clients that are closer to this server than any other, and will not cause a global failure.
[src:ddos-mitigation-deep/anycast] However, even the automation necessary to implement "heartbeat" routing withdrawal can itself add a potential point of failure, as seen in the 2021 Facebook outage.
[src:ddos-mitigation-deep/anycast] In denial-of-service attacks, a rogue network host may advertise itself as an anycast server for a vital network service, to provide false information or simply block service.
[src:ddos-mitigation-deep/anycast] Anycast methodologies on the Internet may be exploited to distribute DDoS attacks and reduce their effectiveness: As traffic is routed to the closest node, a process over which the attacker has no control, the DDoS traffic flow will be distributed amongst the closest nodes.
[src:ddos-mitigation-deep/anycast] This may be a reason to deploy anycast addressing.
[src:ddos-mitigation-deep/anycast] The effectiveness of this technique depends upon maintaining the secrecy of any unicast addresses associated with anycast service nodes, however, since an attacker in possession of the unicast addresses of individual nodes can attack them from any location, bypassing anycast addressing methods.
[src:ddos-mitigation-deep/anycast] Some anycast deployments on the Internet distinguish between local and global nodes to benefit the local community, by addressing local nodes preferentially.
[src:ddos-mitigation-deep/anycast] Local nodes are often announced with the no-export BGP community to prevent hosts from announcing them to their peers, i.e. the announcement is kept in the local area.
[src:ddos-mitigation-deep/anycast] Where both local and global nodes are deployed, the announcements from global nodes are often AS prepended (i.e. the AS is added a few more times) to make the path longer so that a local node announcement is preferred over a global node announcement.
[src:ddos-mitigation-deep/black-hole-networking] In networking, a **black hole** refers to a place in the network where incoming or outgoing traffic is discarded (or "dropped" or sinkholed) without informing the source that the data did not reach its intended recipient.
[src:ddos-mitigation-deep/black-hole-networking] When examining the topology of the network, the black holes themselves are invisible, and can only be detected by monitoring the lost traffic.
[src:ddos-mitigation-deep/black-hole-networking] The name is presumed to have originated from the astronomical body called a black hole - an astronomical body so dense that its gravity prevents anything from escaping, even light.
[src:ddos-mitigation-deep/black-hole-networking] A black hole IP address specifies a host machine that is not running or an address to which no host has been assigned.
[src:ddos-mitigation-deep/black-hole-networking] Even though TCP/IP provides a means of communicating the delivery failure back to the sender via ICMP, traffic destined for such addresses is often just dropped.
[src:ddos-mitigation-deep/black-hole-networking] Blackholed addresses are undetectable only to protocols that are both connectionless and unreliable (e.g., UDP).
[src:ddos-mitigation-deep/black-hole-networking] Connection-oriented or reliable protocols (TCP, RUDP) will either fail to connect to a blackholed address or will fail to receive expected acknowledgements.
[src:ddos-mitigation-deep/black-hole-networking] For IPv4, no black hole address is explicitly defined, however the reserved IP addresses can help achieve a similar effect.
[src:ddos-mitigation-deep/black-hole-networking] For example, *198.51.100.0/24* is reserved for use in documentation and examples; while the RFC advises that the addresses in this range are not routed, this is not a requirement.
[src:ddos-mitigation-deep/black-hole-networking] With the invention of cryptocurrencies addresses as locations where monies exist, there is the possibility of blackholing a quantity of crypto.
[src:ddos-mitigation-deep/black-hole-networking] Most firewalls (and routers for household use) can be configured to silently discard packets addressed to forbidden hosts or ports, resulting in small or large "black holes" in the network.
[src:ddos-mitigation-deep/black-hole-networking] Personal firewalls that do not respond to ICMP echo requests ("ping") have been designated by some vendors as being in "stealth mode".
[src:ddos-mitigation-deep/black-hole-networking] Despite this, in most networks the IP addresses of hosts with firewalls configured in this way are easily distinguished from invalid or otherwise unreachable IP addresses: On encountering the latter, a router will generally respond with an ICMP network rsp. host unreachable error.
[src:ddos-mitigation-deep/black-hole-networking] Network address translation (NAT), as used in home and office routers, is generally a more effective way of obscuring the layout of an internal network.
[src:ddos-mitigation-deep/black-hole-networking] Some firewalls incorrectly discard all ICMP packets, including the ones needed for Path MTU discovery to work correctly.
[src:ddos-mitigation-deep/black-hole-networking] This causes TCP connections from/to/through hosts with a lower MTU to hang.
[src:ddos-mitigation-deep/black-hole-networking] A **null route** or **black hole route** is a network route (routing table entry) that goes nowhere.
[src:ddos-mitigation-deep/black-hole-networking] Matching packets are dropped (ignored) rather than forwarded, acting as a kind of very limited firewall.
[src:ddos-mitigation-deep/black-hole-networking] The act of using null routes is often called **blackhole filtering**.
[src:ddos-mitigation-deep/black-hole-networking] Black hole filtering refers specifically to dropping packets at the routing level, usually using a routing protocol to implement the filtering on several routers at once, often dynamically to respond quickly to distributed denial-of-service attacks (DDoS).
[src:ddos-mitigation-deep/black-hole-networking] Remote Triggered Black Hole Filtering (RTBH) is a technique that provides the ability to drop undesirable traffic before it enters a protected network.
[src:ddos-mitigation-deep/black-hole-networking] The Internet Exchange (IX) provider usually acquires this technology to help its members or participants to filter such attacks.
[src:ddos-mitigation-deep/black-hole-networking] Null routes are typically configured with a special route flag; for example, the standard iproute2 command `ip route` allows to set route types `unreachable, blackhole, prohibit` which discard packets.
[src:ddos-mitigation-deep/black-hole-networking] Alternatively, a null route can be implemented by forwarding packets to an illegal IP address such as *0.0.0.0*, or the loopback address.
[src:ddos-mitigation-deep/black-hole-networking] Null routing has an advantage over classic firewalls since it is available on every potential network router (including all modern operating systems), and adds virtually no performance impact.
[src:ddos-mitigation-deep/black-hole-networking] Due to the nature of high-bandwidth routers, null routing can often sustain higher throughput than conventional firewalls.
[src:ddos-mitigation-deep/black-hole-networking] For this reason, null routes are often used on high-performance core routers to mitigate large-scale denial-of-service attacks before the packets reach a bottleneck, thus avoiding collateral damage from DDoS attacks — although the target of the attack will be inaccessible to anyone.
[src:ddos-mitigation-deep/black-hole-networking] Blackhole filtering can also be abused by malicious attackers on compromised routers to filter out traffic destined to a certain address.
[src:ddos-mitigation-deep/black-hole-networking] Routing typically only works on the Internet Protocol layer and is very limited in packet classification.
[src:ddos-mitigation-deep/black-hole-networking] It is bound to be stateless due to the nature of IP routers.
[src:ddos-mitigation-deep/black-hole-networking] Typically, classification is limited to the destination IP address prefix, source IP address and incoming network interface.
[src:ddos-mitigation-deep/black-hole-networking] A **DNS-based Blackhole List** (**DNSBL**) or **Real-time Blackhole List** (**RBL**) is a list of IP addresses published through the Internet Domain Name System (DNS) either as a zone file that can be used by DNS server software, or as a live DNS zone that can be queried in real-time.
[src:ddos-mitigation-deep/black-hole-networking] DNSBLs are most often used to publish the addresses of computers or networks linked to spamming; most mail server software can be configured to reject or flag messages which have been sent from a site listed on one or more such lists.
[src:ddos-mitigation-deep/black-hole-networking] The term "Blackhole List" is sometimes interchanged with the term "blacklist" and "blocklist".
[src:ddos-mitigation-deep/black-hole-networking] A black hole e-mail address is an e-mail address which is valid (messages sent to it will not generate errors), but all the received messages are automatically deleted, and never stored or seen by humans.
[src:ddos-mitigation-deep/black-hole-networking] These addresses are often used as return addresses for automated e-mails.
[src:ddos-mitigation-deep/content-delivery-network] A **content delivery network** (**CDN**) or **content distribution network** is a geographically distributed network of proxy servers and corresponding data centers.
[src:ddos-mitigation-deep/content-delivery-network] CDNs provide high availability and performance ("speed") through geographical distribution relative to end users, and arose in the late 1990s to alleviate the performance bottlenecks of the Internet as it was becoming a critical medium.
[src:ddos-mitigation-deep/content-delivery-network] Since then, CDNs have grown to serve a large portion of Internet content, including text, graphics and scripts, downloadable objects (media files, software, and documents), applications (e-commerce, portals), live streaming media, on-demand streaming media, and social media services.
[src:ddos-mitigation-deep/content-delivery-network] CDNs are a layer in the internet ecosystem.
[src:ddos-mitigation-deep/content-delivery-network] Content owners such as media companies and e-commerce vendors pay CDN operators to deliver their content to their end users.
[src:ddos-mitigation-deep/content-delivery-network] In turn, a CDN pays Internet service providers (ISPs), carriers, and network operators for hosting its servers in their data centers.
[src:ddos-mitigation-deep/content-delivery-network] CDN vendors may cross over into other industries like security, DDoS protection and web application firewalls (WAF), and WAN optimization.
[src:ddos-mitigation-deep/content-delivery-network] Content delivery service providers include Akamai Technologies, Cloudflare, Amazon CloudFront, Qwilt (Cisco), Fastly, CDN77, BunnyCDN, EdgeNext, and Google Cloud CDN.
[src:ddos-mitigation-deep/content-delivery-network] CDN nodes are usually deployed in multiple locations, often over multiple Internet backbones.
[src:ddos-mitigation-deep/content-delivery-network] Benefits include reducing bandwidth costs, improving page load times, and increasing the global availability of content.
[src:ddos-mitigation-deep/content-delivery-network] The number of nodes and servers making up a CDN varies, depending on the architecture, some reaching thousands of nodes with tens of thousands of servers on many remote points of presence (PoPs).
[src:ddos-mitigation-deep/content-delivery-network] Others build a global network and have a small number of geographical PoPs.
[src:ddos-mitigation-deep/content-delivery-network] Requests for content are typically algorithmically directed to nodes that are optimal in some way.
[src:ddos-mitigation-deep/content-delivery-network] When optimizing for performance, locations that are best for serving content to the user may be chosen.
[src:ddos-mitigation-deep/content-delivery-network] This may be measured by choosing locations that are the fewest hops or the shortest time to the requesting client, or the highest server performance, to optimize delivery across local networks.
[src:ddos-mitigation-deep/content-delivery-network] When optimizing for cost, locations that are the least expensive may be chosen instead.
[src:ddos-mitigation-deep/content-delivery-network] In an optimal scenario, these two goals tend to align, as **edge servers** that are close to the end user at the edge of the network may have an advantage in performance and cost.
[src:ddos-mitigation-deep/content-delivery-network] Most CDN providers will provide their services over a varying, defined, set of PoPs, depending on the coverage desired, such as United States, Asia-Pacific, International or Global, etc.
[src:ddos-mitigation-deep/content-delivery-network] These sets of PoPs can be called "edges", "edge nodes", "edge servers", or "edge networks" as they would be the closest edge of CDN assets to the end user.
[src:ddos-mitigation-deep/content-delivery-network] CDN providers profit either from direct fees paid by content providers using their network, or profit from the user analytics and tracking data collected as their scripts are being loaded onto customers' websites inside their browser origin.
[src:ddos-mitigation-deep/content-delivery-network] As such these services are being pointed out as potential privacy intrusions for the purpose of behavioral targeting and solutions are being created to restore single-origin serving and caching of resources.
[src:ddos-mitigation-deep/content-delivery-network] In particular, a website using a CDN may violate the EU's General Data Protection Regulation (GDPR).
[src:ddos-mitigation-deep/content-delivery-network] For example, in 2021 a German court forbade the use of a CDN on a university website, because this caused the transmission of the user's IP address to the CDN, which violated the GDPR.
[src:ddos-mitigation-deep/content-delivery-network] CDNs serving JavaScript have also been targeted as a way to inject malicious content into pages using them.
[src:ddos-mitigation-deep/content-delivery-network] Subresource Integrity mechanism was created in response to ensure that the page loads a script whose content is known and constrained to a hash referenced by the website author.
[src:ddos-mitigation-deep/content-delivery-network] The Internet was designed according to the end-to-end principle.
[src:ddos-mitigation-deep/content-delivery-network] This principle keeps the core network relatively simple and moves the intelligence as much as possible to the network end-points: the hosts and clients.
[src:ddos-mitigation-deep/content-delivery-network] As a result, the core network is specialized, optimized, and simplified to only forward data packets.
[src:ddos-mitigation-deep/content-delivery-network] Content Delivery Networks extend the transport network by distributing on it a variety of intelligent applications employing techniques designed to optimize content delivery.
[src:ddos-mitigation-deep/content-delivery-network] The resulting tightly integrated overlay uses web caching, server-load balancing, request routing, and content services.
[src:ddos-mitigation-deep/content-delivery-network] Web caches store popular content on servers that have the greatest demand for the content requested.
[src:ddos-mitigation-deep/content-delivery-network] These shared network appliances reduce bandwidth requirements, reduce server load, and improve the client response times for content stored in the cache.
[src:ddos-mitigation-deep/content-delivery-network] Web caches are populated based on requests from users (pull caching) or based on preloaded content disseminated from content servers (push caching).
[src:ddos-mitigation-deep/content-delivery-network] Server-load balancing uses one or more techniques including service-based (global load balancing) or hardware-based (i.e. layer 4–7 switches, also known as a web switch, content switch, or multilayer switch) to share traffic among a number of servers or web caches.
[src:ddos-mitigation-deep/content-delivery-network] Here the switch is assigned a single virtual IP address.
[src:ddos-mitigation-deep/content-delivery-network] Traffic arriving at the switch is then directed to one of the real web servers attached to the switch.
[src:ddos-mitigation-deep/content-delivery-network] This has the advantage of balancing load, increasing total capacity, improving scalability, and providing increased reliability by redistributing the load of a failed web server and providing server health checks.
[src:ddos-mitigation-deep/content-delivery-network] A content cluster or service node can be formed using a layer 4–7 switch to balance load across a number of servers or a number of web caches within the network.
[src:ddos-mitigation-deep/content-delivery-network] Request routing directs client requests to the content source best able to serve the request.
[src:ddos-mitigation-deep/content-delivery-network] This may involve directing a client request to the service node that is closest to the client, or to the one with the most capacity.
[src:ddos-mitigation-deep/content-delivery-network] A variety of algorithms are used to route the request.
[src:ddos-mitigation-deep/content-delivery-network] These include Global Server Load Balancing, DNS-based request routing, Dynamic metafile generation, HTML rewriting, and anycasting.
[src:ddos-mitigation-deep/content-delivery-network] Proximity—choosing the closest service node—is estimated using a variety of techniques including reactive probing, proactive probing, and connection monitoring.
[src:ddos-mitigation-deep/content-delivery-network] CDNs use a variety of methods of content delivery including, but not limited to, manual asset copying, active web caches, and global hardware load balancers.
[src:ddos-mitigation-deep/content-delivery-network] Several protocol suites are designed to provide access to a wide variety of content services distributed throughout a content network.
[src:ddos-mitigation-deep/content-delivery-network] The Internet Content Adaptation Protocol (ICAP) was developed in the late 1990s to provide an open standard for connecting application servers.
[src:ddos-mitigation-deep/content-delivery-network] A more recently defined and robust solution is provided by the Open Pluggable Edge Services (OPES) protocol.
[src:ddos-mitigation-deep/content-delivery-network] This architecture defines OPES service applications that can reside on the OPES processor itself or be executed remotely on a Callout Server.
[src:ddos-mitigation-deep/content-delivery-network] Edge Side Includes or ESI is a small markup language for edge-level dynamic web content assembly.
[src:ddos-mitigation-deep/content-delivery-network] It is fairly common for websites to have generated content.
[src:ddos-mitigation-deep/content-delivery-network] It could be because of changing content like catalogs or forums, or because of the personalization.
[src:ddos-mitigation-deep/content-delivery-network] This creates a problem for caching systems.
[src:ddos-mitigation-deep/content-delivery-network] To overcome this problem, a group of companies created ESI.
[src:ddos-mitigation-deep/content-delivery-network] In *peer-to-peer (P2P)* content-delivery networks, clients provide resources as well as use them.
[src:ddos-mitigation-deep/content-delivery-network] This means that, unlike client–server systems, the content-centric networks can actually perform better as more users begin to access the content (especially with protocols such as Bittorrent that require users to share).
[src:ddos-mitigation-deep/content-delivery-network] This property is one of the major advantages of using P2P networks because it makes the setup and running costs very small for the original content distributor.
[src:ddos-mitigation-deep/content-delivery-network] To incentive peers to participate in the P2P network, web3 and blockchain technologies can be used: participating nodes receive crypto tokens in exchange of their involvement.
[src:ddos-mitigation-deep/content-delivery-network] If content owners are not satisfied with the options or costs of a commercial CDN service, they can create their own CDN.
[src:ddos-mitigation-deep/content-delivery-network] A private CDN consists of PoPs (points of presence) that are only serving content for their owner.
[src:ddos-mitigation-deep/content-delivery-network] These PoPs can be caching servers, reverse proxies or application delivery controllers.
[src:ddos-mitigation-deep/content-delivery-network] It can be as simple as two caching servers, or large enough to serve petabytes of content.
[src:ddos-mitigation-deep/content-delivery-network] When a private CDN is deployed within a company network, it is also referred as Entreprise CDN or **eCDN**.
[src:ddos-mitigation-deep/content-delivery-network] Large content distribution networks may even build and set up their own private network to distribute copies of content across cache locations.
[src:ddos-mitigation-deep/content-delivery-network] Such private networks are usually used in conjunction with public networks as a backup option in case the capacity of the private network is not enough or there is a failure which leads to capacity reduction.
[src:ddos-mitigation-deep/content-delivery-network] Since the same content has to be distributed across many locations, a variety of multicasting techniques may be used to reduce bandwidth consumption.
[src:ddos-mitigation-deep/content-delivery-network] Over private networks, it has also been proposed to select multicast trees according to network load conditions to more efficiently utilize available network capacity.
[src:ddos-mitigation-deep/content-delivery-network] The rapid growth of streaming video traffic required large capital expenditures by broadband providers in order to meet this demand and retain subscribers by delivering a sufficiently good quality of experience.
[src:ddos-mitigation-deep/content-delivery-network] To address this, telecommunications service providers have begun to launch their own content delivery networks as a means to lessen the demands on the network backbone and reduce infrastructure investments.
[src:ddos-mitigation-deep/content-delivery-network] Because they own the networks over which video content is transmitted, telco CDNs have advantages over traditional CDNs.
[src:ddos-mitigation-deep/content-delivery-network] They own the last mile and can deliver content closer to the end-user because it can be cached deep in their networks.
[src:ddos-mitigation-deep/content-delivery-network] This deep caching minimizes the distance that video data travels over the general Internet and delivers it more quickly and reliably.
[src:ddos-mitigation-deep/content-delivery-network] Telco CDNs also have a built-in cost advantage since traditional CDNs must lease bandwidth from them and build the operator's margin into their own cost model.
[src:ddos-mitigation-deep/content-delivery-network] In addition, by operating their own content delivery infrastructure, telco operators have better control over the utilization of their resources.
[src:ddos-mitigation-deep/content-delivery-network] Content management operations performed by CDNs are usually applied without (or with very limited) information about the network (e.g., topology, utilization etc.) of the telco-operators with which they interact or have business relationships.
[src:ddos-mitigation-deep/content-delivery-network] These pose a number of challenges for the telco-operators who have a limited sphere of action in face of the impact of these operations on the utilization of their resources.
[src:ddos-mitigation-deep/content-delivery-network] In contrast, the deployment of telco-CDNs allows operators to implement their own content management operations, which enables them to have a better control over the utilization of their resources and, as such, provide better quality of service and experience to their end users.
[src:ddos-mitigation-deep/content-delivery-network] In June 2011, StreamingMedia.com reported that a group of TSPs had founded an Operator Carrier Exchange (OCX) to interconnect their networks and compete more directly against large traditional CDNs like Akamai and Limelight Networks, which have extensive PoPs worldwide.
[src:ddos-mitigation-deep/content-delivery-network] This way, telcos are building a Federated CDN offering, which is more interesting for a content provider willing to deliver its content to the aggregated audience of this federation.
[src:ddos-mitigation-deep/content-delivery-network] It is likely that in a near future, other telco CDN federations will be created.
[src:ddos-mitigation-deep/content-delivery-network] They will grow by enrollment of new telcos joining the federation and bringing network presence and their Internet subscriber bases to the existing ones.
[src:ddos-mitigation-deep/content-delivery-network] The Open Caching specification by Streaming Video Technology Alliance defines a set of APIs that allows a Content Provider to deliver its content using several CDNs in a consistent way, seeing each CDN provider the same way through these APIs.
[src:ddos-mitigation-deep/content-delivery-network] Combining several CDN services allow Content Providers to not rely on a single CDN service, especially concerned to deal with high peak audience during live events.
[src:ddos-mitigation-deep/content-delivery-network] There are several ways to allocate traffic to a particular CDN among the list, either client-side CDN selection, or server-side (at the Content Provider's origin) or cloud-side (in the middle, between the content origin and the audience).
[src:ddos-mitigation-deep/content-delivery-network] CDN selection criteria can be performance, availability and cost.
[src:ddos-mitigation-deep/content-delivery-network] Traditionally, CDNs have used the IP of the client's recursive DNS resolver to geo-locate the client.
[src:ddos-mitigation-deep/content-delivery-network] While this is a sound approach in many situations, this leads to poor client performance if the client uses a non-local recursive DNS resolver that is far away.
[src:ddos-mitigation-deep/content-delivery-network] For instance, a CDN may route requests from a client in India to its edge server in Singapore, if that client uses a public DNS resolver in Singapore, causing poor performance for that client.
[src:ddos-mitigation-deep/content-delivery-network] Indeed, a recent study showed that in many countries where public DNS resolvers are in popular use, the median distance between the clients and their recursive DNS resolvers can be as high as a thousand miles.
[src:ddos-mitigation-deep/content-delivery-network] In August 2011, a global consortium of leading Internet service providers led by Google announced their official implementation of the edns-client-subnet IETF Internet Draft, which is intended to accurately localize DNS resolution responses.
[src:ddos-mitigation-deep/content-delivery-network] The initiative involves a limited number of leading DNS service providers, such as Google Public DNS, and CDN service providers as well.
[src:ddos-mitigation-deep/content-delivery-network] With the edns-client-subnet EDNS0 option, CDNs can now utilize the IP address of the requesting client's subnet when resolving DNS requests.
[src:ddos-mitigation-deep/content-delivery-network] This approach, called end-user mapping, has been adopted by CDNs and it has been shown to drastically reduce the round-trip latencies and improve performance for clients who use public DNS or other non-local resolvers.
[src:ddos-mitigation-deep/content-delivery-network] However, the use of EDNS0 also has drawbacks as it decreases the effectiveness of caching resolutions at the recursive resolvers, increases the total DNS resolution traffic, and raises a privacy concern of exposing the client's subnet.
[src:ddos-mitigation-deep/content-delivery-network] Virtualization technologies are being used to deploy virtual CDNs (vCDNs) (also known as a software-defined CDN or sd-CDN) with the goal to reduce content provider costs, and at the same time, increase elasticity and decrease service delay.
[src:ddos-mitigation-deep/content-delivery-network] With vCDNs, it is possible to avoid traditional CDN limitations, such as performance, reliability and availability since virtual caches are deployed dynamically (as virtual machines or containers) in physical servers distributed across the provider's geographical coverage.
[src:ddos-mitigation-deep/content-delivery-network] As the virtual cache placement is based on both the content type and server or end-user geographic location, the vCDNs have a significant impact on service delivery and network congestion.
[src:ddos-mitigation-deep/content-delivery-network] To boost performance, delivery to clients from servers can use alternate non-HTTP protocols such as WebRTC and WebSockets.
[src:ddos-mitigation-deep/content-delivery-network] In 2017, Addy Osmani of Google started referring to software solutions that could integrate naturally with the Responsive Web Design paradigm (with particular reference to the <picture> element) as **Image CDN**s.
[src:ddos-mitigation-deep/content-delivery-network] The expression referred to the ability of a web architecture to serve multiple versions of the same image through HTTP, depending on the properties of the browser requesting it, as determined by either the browser or the server-side logic.
[src:ddos-mitigation-deep/content-delivery-network] The purpose of Image CDNs was, in Google's vision, to serve high-quality images (or, better, images perceived as high-quality by the human eye) while preserving download speed, thus contributing to a great User experience (UX).
[src:ddos-mitigation-deep/content-delivery-network] Arguably, the *Image CDN* term was originally a misnomer, as neither Cloudinary nor Imgix (the examples quoted by Google in the 2017 guide by Addy Osmani) were, at the time, a CDN in the classical sense of the term.
[src:ddos-mitigation-deep/content-delivery-network] Shortly afterwards, though, several companies offered solutions that allowed developers to serve different versions of their graphical assets according to several strategies.
[src:ddos-mitigation-deep/content-delivery-network] Many of these solutions were built on top of traditional CDNs, such as Akamai, CloudFront, Fastly, Edgecast and Cloudflare.
[src:ddos-mitigation-deep/content-delivery-network] At the same time, other solutions that already provided an image multi-serving service joined the Image CDN definition by either offering CDN functionality natively (ImageEngine) or integrating with one of the existing CDNs (Cloudinary/Akamai, Imgix/Fastly).
[src:ddos-mitigation-deep/ddos-mitigation] DDoS mitigation works by identifying baseline conditions for network traffic by analyzing "traffic patterns" to allow threat detection and alerting.
[src:ddos-mitigation-deep/ddos-mitigation] DDoS mitigation also requires identifying incoming traffic to separate human traffic from human-like bots and hijacked web browsers.
[src:ddos-mitigation-deep/ddos-mitigation] This process involves comparing signatures and examining different attributes of the traffic, including IP addresses, cookie variations, HTTP headers, and browser fingerprints.
[src:ddos-mitigation-deep/ddos-mitigation] After the attack is detected, the next process is filtering.
[src:ddos-mitigation-deep/ddos-mitigation] Filtering can be done through anti-DDoS technology like connection tracking, IP reputation lists, deep packet inspection, blacklisting/whitelisting, or rate limiting.
[src:ddos-mitigation-deep/ddos-mitigation] One technique is to pass network traffic addressed to a potential target network through high-capacity networks, with "traffic scrubbing" filters.
[src:ddos-mitigation-deep/ddos-mitigation] Manual DDoS mitigation is no longer recommended due to the size of attacks often outstripping the human resources available in many firms/organizations.
[src:ddos-mitigation-deep/ddos-mitigation] Other methods to prevent DDoS attacks can be implemented such as on-premises or cloud-based solution providers.
[src:ddos-mitigation-deep/ddos-mitigation] On-premises mitigation technology (most commonly a hardware device) is often placed in front of the network.
[src:ddos-mitigation-deep/ddos-mitigation] This would limit the maximum bandwidth available to what is provided by the Internet service provider.
[src:ddos-mitigation-deep/ddos-mitigation] Common methods involve hybrid solutions, by combining on-premises filtering with cloud-based solutions.
[src:ddos-mitigation-deep/ddos-mitigation] DDoS attacks are executed against websites and networks of selected victims.
[src:ddos-mitigation-deep/ddos-mitigation] A number of vendors offer "DDoS-resistant" hosting services, mostly based on techniques similar to content delivery networks.
[src:ddos-mitigation-deep/ddos-mitigation] Distribution avoids a single point of congestion and prevents the DDoS attack from concentrating on a single target.
[src:ddos-mitigation-deep/ddos-mitigation] One technique of DDoS attacks is to use misconfigured third-party networks, allowing the amplification of spoofed UDP packets.
[src:ddos-mitigation-deep/ddos-mitigation] Proper configuration of network equipment, enabling ingress filtering and egress filtering, as documented in BCP 38 and RFC 6959, prevents amplification and spoofing, thus reducing the number of relay networks available to attackers.
[src:ddos-mitigation-deep/ddos-mitigation] DDoS attacks are typically categorized into three types: volumetric, protocol-based, and application-layer attacks.
[src:ddos-mitigation-deep/ddos-mitigation] These attacks aim to consume bandwidth by flooding a network or service with massive volumes of traffic.
[src:ddos-mitigation-deep/ddos-mitigation] These focus on exhausting resources of network infrastructure by misusing communication protocol behavior.
[src:ddos-mitigation-deep/ddos-mitigation] These attacks mimic legitimate traffic to deplete application server resources, making them particularly difficult to detect.
[src:ddos-mitigation-deep/ddos-mitigation] DDoS mitigation defenses such as traffic scrubbing, rate limiting, and content delivery networks require continuous validation to confirm they are performing as intended.
[src:ddos-mitigation-deep/ddos-mitigation] Mitigation tools can produce false positives, blocking legitimate users by misidentifying their traffic as malicious, and gaps in filtering rules can go undetected until an actual attack causes service disruption.
[src:ddos-mitigation-deep/ddos-mitigation] This type of testing also generates auditable reporting that aligns DDoS risk management with business continuity and regulatory objectives.
[src:ddos-mitigation-deep/denial-of-service-attack] In computing, a **denial-of-service attack** (**DoS attack** /dɒs/ *doss*) is a cyberattack in which the perpetrator seeks to make a machine or network resource unavailable to its intended users by temporarily or indefinitely disrupting services of a host connected to a network.
[src:ddos-mitigation-deep/denial-of-service-attack] Denial of service is typically accomplished by flooding the targeted machine or resource with superfluous requests in an attempt to overload systems and prevent some or all legitimate requests from being fulfilled.
[src:ddos-mitigation-deep/denial-of-service-attack] The range of attacks varies widely, spanning from inundating a server with millions of requests to slow its performance, overwhelming a server with a substantial amount of invalid data, to submitting requests with an illegitimate IP address.
[src:ddos-mitigation-deep/denial-of-service-attack] In a **distributed denial-of-service attack** (**DDoS attack** /ˈdiː.dɒs/ *DEE-doss*), the incoming traffic flooding the victim originates from many different sources.
[src:ddos-mitigation-deep/denial-of-service-attack] More sophisticated strategies are required to mitigate this type of attack; simply attempting to block a single source is insufficient.
[src:ddos-mitigation-deep/denial-of-service-attack] A DDoS attack is analogous to a group of people crowding the entry door of a shop, making it hard for legitimate customers to enter, thus disrupting trade and losing the business money.
[src:ddos-mitigation-deep/denial-of-service-attack] Criminal perpetrators of DDoS attacks often target sites or services hosted on high-profile web servers such as banks or credit card payment gateways.
[src:ddos-mitigation-deep/denial-of-service-attack] Revenge and blackmail, as well as hacktivism, can motivate these attacks.
[src:ddos-mitigation-deep/denial-of-service-attack] Panix, the third-oldest Internet service provider (ISP) in the world, was the target of what is thought to be the first DoS attack.
[src:ddos-mitigation-deep/denial-of-service-attack] On September 6, 1996, Panix was subject to a SYN flood attack, which brought down its services for several days while hardware vendors, notably Cisco, figured out a proper defense.
[src:ddos-mitigation-deep/denial-of-service-attack] The release of sample code during the event led to the online attack of Sprint, EarthLink, E-Trade, and other major corporations in the year to follow.
[src:ddos-mitigation-deep/denial-of-service-attack] In February 2020, Amazon Web Services experienced an attack with a peak volume of 2.3 Tb/s.
[src:ddos-mitigation-deep/denial-of-service-attack] In July 2021, Cloudflare boasted of protecting its client from a DDoS attack from a global Mirai botnet that was up to 17.2 million requests per second.
[src:ddos-mitigation-deep/denial-of-service-attack] Russian DDoS prevention provider Yandex said it blocked an HTTP pipelining DDoS attack on Sept.
[src:ddos-mitigation-deep/denial-of-service-attack] 2021 that originated from unpatched Mikrotik networking gear.
[src:ddos-mitigation-deep/denial-of-service-attack] In the first half of 2022, the Russian invasion of Ukraine significantly shaped the cyberthreat landscape, with an increase in cyberattacks attributed to both state-sponsored actors and global hacktivist activities.
[src:ddos-mitigation-deep/denial-of-service-attack] The most notable event was a DDoS attack in February, the largest Ukraine has encountered, disrupting government and financial sector services.
[src:ddos-mitigation-deep/denial-of-service-attack] This wave of cyber aggression extended to Western allies like the UK, the US, and Germany.
[src:ddos-mitigation-deep/denial-of-service-attack] Particularly, the UK's financial sector saw an increase in DDoS attacks from nation-state actors and hacktivists, aimed at undermining Ukraine's allies.
[src:ddos-mitigation-deep/denial-of-service-attack] In February 2023, Cloudflare faced a 71 million requests per second attack which they claimed was the largest HTTP DDoS attack at the time.
[src:ddos-mitigation-deep/denial-of-service-attack] HTTP DDoS attacks are measured by HTTP requests per second instead of packets per second or bits per second.
[src:ddos-mitigation-deep/denial-of-service-attack] On July 10, 2023, the fanfiction platform Archive of Our Own (AO3) faced DDoS attacks, disrupting services.
[src:ddos-mitigation-deep/denial-of-service-attack] Anonymous Sudan, claiming the attack for religious and political reasons, was viewed skeptically by AO3 and experts.
[src:ddos-mitigation-deep/denial-of-service-attack] Flashpoint, a threat intelligence vendor, noted the group's past activities but doubted their stated motives.
[src:ddos-mitigation-deep/denial-of-service-attack] AO3, supported by the non-profit Organization for Transformative Works (OTW) and reliant on donations, is unlikely to meet the $30,000 Bitcoin ransom.
[src:ddos-mitigation-deep/denial-of-service-attack] In August 2023, the group of hacktivists NoName057 targeted several Italian financial institutions, through the execution of slow DoS attacks.
[src:ddos-mitigation-deep/denial-of-service-attack] On 14 January 2024, they executed a DDoS attack on Swiss federal websites, prompted by President Zelensky's attendance at the Davos World Economic Forum.
[src:ddos-mitigation-deep/denial-of-service-attack] Switzerland's National Cyber Security Centre quickly mitigated the attack, ensuring core federal services remained secure, despite temporary accessibility issues on some websites.
[src:ddos-mitigation-deep/denial-of-service-attack] In October 2023, exploitation of a new vulnerability in the HTTP/2 protocol resulted in the record for largest HTTP DDoS attack being broken twice, once with a 201 million requests per second attack observed by Cloudflare, and again with a 398 million requests per second attack observed by Google.
[src:ddos-mitigation-deep/denial-of-service-attack] In August 2024, Global Secure Layer observed and reported on a record-breaking packet DDoS at 3.15 billion packets per second, which targeted an undisclosed number of unofficial Minecraft game servers.
[src:ddos-mitigation-deep/denial-of-service-attack] In October 2024, the Internet Archive faced two severe DDoS attacks that brought the site completely offline, immediately following a previous attack that leaked records of over 31 million of the site's users.
[src:ddos-mitigation-deep/denial-of-service-attack] The hacktivist group SN_Blackmeta claimed the DDoS attack as retribution for American involvement in the Gaza war, despite the Internet Archive being unaffiliated with the United States government; however, their link with the preceding data leak remains unclear.
[src:ddos-mitigation-deep/denial-of-service-attack] Cloudflare claims to have recorded and successfully autonomously blocked a 40-second DDoS attack on 23 September 2025, that reached a peak volume of 22.2 Tbit/s, which would be the largest DDoS attack to date.
[src:ddos-mitigation-deep/denial-of-service-attack] Cloudflare has stated that over 404,000 source IPs were used to target one IP address, and that the source IPs were not spoofed.
[src:ddos-mitigation-deep/denial-of-service-attack] According to Cloudflare, this came after several other large-scale DDoS attacks, each consecutively beating the previous record, including a 7.3 Tbit/s attack in May 2025 and an 11.5 Tbit/s attack on 1 September 2025.
[src:ddos-mitigation-deep/denial-of-service-attack] Denial-of-service attacks are characterized by an explicit attempt by attackers to prevent legitimate use of a service.
[src:ddos-mitigation-deep/denial-of-service-attack] There are two general forms of DoS attacks: those that crash services and those that flood services.
[src:ddos-mitigation-deep/denial-of-service-attack] The most serious attacks are distributed.
[src:ddos-mitigation-deep/denial-of-service-attack] A distributed denial-of-service (DDoS) attack occurs when multiple systems flood the bandwidth or resources of a targeted system, usually one or more web servers.
[src:ddos-mitigation-deep/denial-of-service-attack] A DDoS attack uses more than one unique IP address or machines, often from thousands of hosts infected with malware.
[src:ddos-mitigation-deep/denial-of-service-attack] A distributed denial of service attack typically involves more than around 3–5 nodes on different networks; fewer nodes may qualify as a DoS attack but is not a DDoS attack.
[src:ddos-mitigation-deep/denial-of-service-attack] Most of the time, attackers operate from an endpoint that is not their intended target, for example using another user's machine to attack a server.
[src:ddos-mitigation-deep/denial-of-service-attack] By using another unsuspecting endpoint if it becomes compromised they can then move onto another workstation within the enterprise network.
[src:ddos-mitigation-deep/denial-of-service-attack] However, even faking lots of users and executing a DoS attack, a single attacker with few computers is still very limited in the amount of traffic they can generate.
[src:ddos-mitigation-deep/denial-of-service-attack] If the attacks are from multiple sources, it can be difficult for the host to identify and stop them.
[src:ddos-mitigation-deep/denial-of-service-attack] The scale of DDoS attacks has continued to rise over recent years, by 2016 exceeding a terabit per second.
[src:ddos-mitigation-deep/denial-of-service-attack] Some common examples of DDoS attacks are UDP flooding, SYN flooding and DNS amplification.
[src:ddos-mitigation-deep/denial-of-service-attack] A **yo-yo attack** is a specific type of DoS/DDoS aimed at cloud-hosted applications which use autoscaling.
[src:ddos-mitigation-deep/denial-of-service-attack] During the attack, an attacker repeatedly changes between sending a lot of traffic (which causes a scale-up) and stopping the burst (causing a scale-down as a result).
[src:ddos-mitigation-deep/denial-of-service-attack] An **application layer DDoS attack** (sometimes referred to as **layer 7 DDoS attack**) is a form of DDoS attack where attackers target application-layer processes.
[src:ddos-mitigation-deep/denial-of-service-attack] The attack over-exercises specific functions or features of a website with the intention to disable those functions or features.
[src:ddos-mitigation-deep/denial-of-service-attack] This application-layer attack is different from an entire network attack, and is often used against financial institutions to distract IT and security personnel from security breaches.
[src:ddos-mitigation-deep/denial-of-service-attack] In 2013, application-layer DDoS attacks represented 20% of all DDoS attacks.
[src:ddos-mitigation-deep/denial-of-service-attack] According to research by Akamai Technologies, there have been "51 percent more application layer attacks" from Q4 2013 to Q4 2014 and "16 percent more" from Q3 2014 to Q4 2014.
[src:ddos-mitigation-deep/denial-of-service-attack] In November 2017; Junade Ali, an engineer at Cloudflare noted that whilst network-level attacks continue to be of high capacity, they were occurring less frequently.
[src:ddos-mitigation-deep/denial-of-service-attack] Ali further noted that although network-level attacks were becoming less frequent, data from Cloudflare demonstrated that application-layer attacks were still showing no sign of slowing down.
[src:ddos-mitigation-deep/denial-of-service-attack] The simplest DoS attack relies primarily on brute force, flooding the target with an overwhelming flux of packets, oversaturating its connection bandwidth or depleting the target's system resources.
[src:ddos-mitigation-deep/denial-of-service-attack] Bandwidth-saturating floods rely on the attacker's ability to generate the overwhelming flux of packets.
[src:ddos-mitigation-deep/denial-of-service-attack] A common way of achieving this today is via distributed denial-of-service, employing a botnet.
[src:ddos-mitigation-deep/denial-of-service-attack] An application layer DDoS attack is done mainly for specific targeted purposes, including disrupting transactions and access to databases.
[src:ddos-mitigation-deep/denial-of-service-attack] It requires fewer resources than network layer attacks but often accompanies them.
[src:ddos-mitigation-deep/denial-of-service-attack] An attack may be disguised to look like legitimate traffic, except it targets specific application packets or functions.
[src:ddos-mitigation-deep/denial-of-service-attack] The attack on the application layer can disrupt services such as the retrieval of information or search functions on a website.
[src:ddos-mitigation-deep/denial-of-service-attack] An **advanced persistent DoS** (APDoS) is associated with an advanced persistent threat and requires specialized DDoS mitigation.
[src:ddos-mitigation-deep/denial-of-service-attack] These attacks can persist for weeks; the longest continuous period noted so far lasted 38 days.
[src:ddos-mitigation-deep/denial-of-service-attack] This attack involved approximately 50+ petabits (50,000+ terabits) of malicious traffic.
[src:ddos-mitigation-deep/denial-of-service-attack] Attackers in this scenario may tactically switch between several targets to create a diversion to evade defensive DDoS countermeasures but all the while eventually concentrating the main thrust of the attack onto a single victim.
[src:ddos-mitigation-deep/denial-of-service-attack] In this scenario, attackers with continuous access to several very powerful network resources are capable of sustaining a prolonged campaign generating enormous levels of unamplified DDoS traffic.
[src:ddos-mitigation-deep/denial-of-service-attack] Some vendors provide so-called *booter* or *stresser* services, which have simple web-based front ends, and accept payment over the web.
[src:ddos-mitigation-deep/denial-of-service-attack] Marketed and promoted as stress-testing tools, they can be used to perform unauthorized denial-of-service attacks, and allow technically unsophisticated attackers access to sophisticated attack tools.
[src:ddos-mitigation-deep/denial-of-service-attack] Usually powered by a botnet, the traffic produced by a consumer stresser can range anywhere from 5-50 Gbit/s, which can, in most cases, deny the average home user internet access.
[src:ddos-mitigation-deep/denial-of-service-attack] A Markov-modulated denial-of-service attack occurs when the attacker disrupts control packets using a hidden Markov model.
[src:ddos-mitigation-deep/denial-of-service-attack] A setting in which Markov-model-based attacks are prevalent is online gaming as the disruption of the control packet undermines gameplay and system functionality.
[src:ddos-mitigation-deep/denial-of-service-attack] In cases such as MyDoom and Slowloris, the tools are embedded in malware and launch their attacks without the knowledge of the system owner.
[src:ddos-mitigation-deep/denial-of-service-attack] Stacheldraht is a classic example of a DDoS tool.
[src:ddos-mitigation-deep/denial-of-service-attack] It uses a layered structure where the attacker uses a client program to connect to handlers which are compromised systems that issue commands to the zombie agents which in turn facilitate the DDoS attack.
[src:ddos-mitigation-deep/denial-of-service-attack] Agents are compromised via the handlers by the attacker using automated routines to exploit vulnerabilities in programs that accept remote connections running on the targeted remote hosts.
[src:ddos-mitigation-deep/denial-of-service-attack] Each handler can control up to a thousand agents.
[src:ddos-mitigation-deep/denial-of-service-attack] In other cases a machine may become part of a DDoS attack with the owner's consent, for example, in Operation Payback organized by the group Anonymous.
[src:ddos-mitigation-deep/denial-of-service-attack] The Low Orbit Ion Cannon has typically been used in this way.
[src:ddos-mitigation-deep/denial-of-service-attack] Along with High Orbit Ion Cannon a wide variety of DDoS tools are available today, including paid and free versions, with different features available.
[src:ddos-mitigation-deep/denial-of-service-attack] There is an underground market for these in hacker-related forums and IRC channels.
[src:ddos-mitigation-deep/denial-of-service-attack] Application-layer attacks employ DoS-causing exploits and can cause server-running software to fill the disk space or consume all available memory or CPU time.
[src:ddos-mitigation-deep/denial-of-service-attack] Attacks may use specific packet types or connection requests to saturate finite resources by, for example, occupying the maximum number of open connections or filling the victim's disk space with logs.
[src:ddos-mitigation-deep/denial-of-service-attack] An attacker with shell-level access to a victim's computer may slow it until it is unusable or crash it by using a fork bomb.
[src:ddos-mitigation-deep/denial-of-service-attack] Another kind of application-level DoS attack is XDoS (or XML DoS) which can be controlled by modern web application firewalls (WAFs).
[src:ddos-mitigation-deep/denial-of-service-attack] All attacks belonging to the category of *timeout exploiting*.
[src:ddos-mitigation-deep/denial-of-service-attack] Slow DoS attacks implement an application-layer attack.
[src:ddos-mitigation-deep/denial-of-service-attack] Examples of threats are Slowloris, establishing pending connections with the victim, or SlowDroid, an attack running on mobile devices.
[src:ddos-mitigation-deep/denial-of-service-attack] Another target of DDoS attacks may be to produce added costs for the application operator, when the latter uses resources based on cloud computing.
[src:ddos-mitigation-deep/denial-of-service-attack] In this case, normally application-used resources are tied to a needed quality of service (QoS) level (e.g. responses should be less than 200 ms) and this rule is usually linked to automated software (e.g.
[src:ddos-mitigation-deep/denial-of-service-attack] Amazon CloudWatch) to raise more virtual resources from the provider to meet the defined QoS levels for the increased requests.
[src:ddos-mitigation-deep/denial-of-service-attack] The main incentive behind such attacks may be to drive the application owner to raise the elasticity levels to handle the increased application traffic, to cause financial losses, or force them to become less competitive.
[src:ddos-mitigation-deep/denial-of-service-attack] A *banana attack* is another particular type of DoS.
[src:ddos-mitigation-deep/denial-of-service-attack] It involves redirecting outgoing messages from the client back onto the client, preventing outside access, as well as flooding the client with the sent packets.
[src:ddos-mitigation-deep/denial-of-service-attack] Pulsing zombies are compromised computers that are directed to launch intermittent and short-lived flooding of victim websites with the intent of merely slowing it rather than crashing it.
[src:ddos-mitigation-deep/denial-of-service-attack] This type of attack, referred to as *degradation-of-service*, can be more difficult to detect and can disrupt and hamper connection to websites for prolonged periods of time, potentially causing more overall disruption than a denial-of-service attack.
[src:ddos-mitigation-deep/denial-of-service-attack] Exposure of degradation-of-service attacks is complicated further by the matter of discerning whether the server is really being attacked or is experiencing higher than normal legitimate traffic loads.
[src:ddos-mitigation-deep/denial-of-service-attack] If an attacker mounts an attack from a single host, it would be classified as a DoS attack.
[src:ddos-mitigation-deep/denial-of-service-attack] Any attack against availability would be classed as a denial-of-service attack.
[src:ddos-mitigation-deep/denial-of-service-attack] On the other hand, if an attacker uses many systems to simultaneously launch attacks against a remote host, this would be classified as a DDoS attack.
[src:ddos-mitigation-deep/denial-of-service-attack] Malware can carry DDoS attack mechanisms; one of the better-known examples of this was MyDoom.
[src:ddos-mitigation-deep/denial-of-service-attack] Its DoS mechanism was triggered on a specific date and time.
[src:ddos-mitigation-deep/denial-of-service-attack] This type of DDoS involved hardcoding the target IP address before releasing the malware and no further interaction was necessary to launch the attack.
[src:ddos-mitigation-deep/denial-of-service-attack] A system may also be compromised with a trojan containing a zombie agent.
[src:ddos-mitigation-deep/denial-of-service-attack] Attackers can also break into systems using automated tools that exploit flaws in programs that listen for connections from remote hosts.
[src:ddos-mitigation-deep/denial-of-service-attack] This scenario primarily concerns systems acting as servers on the web.
[src:ddos-mitigation-deep/denial-of-service-attack] It uses a layered structure where the attacker uses a client program to connect to handlers, which are compromised systems that issue commands to the zombie agents, which in turn facilitate the DDoS attack.
[src:ddos-mitigation-deep/denial-of-service-attack] Agents are compromised via the handlers by the attacker.
[src:ddos-mitigation-deep/denial-of-service-attack] In some cases a machine may become part of a DDoS attack with the owner's consent, for example, in Operation Payback, organized by the group Anonymous.
[src:ddos-mitigation-deep/denial-of-service-attack] These attacks can use different types of internet packets such as TCP, UDP, ICMP, etc.
[src:ddos-mitigation-deep/denial-of-service-attack] These collections of compromised systems are known as botnets.
[src:ddos-mitigation-deep/denial-of-service-attack] DDoS tools like Stacheldraht still use classic DoS attack methods centered on IP spoofing and amplification like smurf attacks and fraggle attacks (types of bandwidth consumption attacks).
[src:ddos-mitigation-deep/denial-of-service-attack] SYN floods (a resource starvation attack) may also be used.
[src:ddos-mitigation-deep/denial-of-service-attack] Newer tools can use DNS servers for DoS purposes.
[src:ddos-mitigation-deep/denial-of-service-attack] Unlike MyDoom's DDoS mechanism, botnets can be turned against any IP address.
[src:ddos-mitigation-deep/denial-of-service-attack] Script kiddies use them to deny the availability of well known websites to legitimate users.
[src:ddos-mitigation-deep/denial-of-service-attack] More sophisticated attackers use DDoS tools for the purposes of extortion – including against their business rivals.
[src:ddos-mitigation-deep/denial-of-service-attack] It has been reported that there are new attacks from internet of things (IoT) devices that have been involved in denial of service attacks.
[src:ddos-mitigation-deep/denial-of-service-attack] One such attack peaked at around 20,000 requests per second; it came from around 900 CCTV cameras.
[src:ddos-mitigation-deep/denial-of-service-attack] UK's GCHQ has tools built for DDoS, named PREDATORS FACE and ROLLING THUNDER.
[src:ddos-mitigation-deep/denial-of-service-attack] Simple attacks such as SYN floods may appear with a wide range of source IP addresses, giving the appearance of a distributed DoS.
[src:ddos-mitigation-deep/denial-of-service-attack] These flood attacks do not require completion of the TCP three-way handshake and attempt to exhaust the destination SYN queue or the server bandwidth.
[src:ddos-mitigation-deep/denial-of-service-attack] Because the source IP addresses can be trivially spoofed, an attack could come from a limited set of sources, or may even originate from a single host.
[src:ddos-mitigation-deep/denial-of-service-attack] Stack enhancements such as SYN cookies may be effective mitigation against SYN queue flooding but do not address bandwidth exhaustion.
[src:ddos-mitigation-deep/denial-of-service-attack] In 2022, TCP attacks were the leading method in DDoS incidents, accounting for 63% of all DDoS activity.
[src:ddos-mitigation-deep/denial-of-service-attack] This includes tactics like TCP SYN, TCP ACK, and TCP floods.
[src:ddos-mitigation-deep/denial-of-service-attack] With TCP being the most widespread networking protocol, its attacks are expected to remain prevalent in the DDoS threat scene.
[src:ddos-mitigation-deep/denial-of-service-attack] In 2015, DDoS botnets such as DD4BC grew in prominence, taking aim at financial institutions.
[src:ddos-mitigation-deep/denial-of-service-attack] Cyber-extortionists typically begin with a low-level attack and a warning that a larger attack will be carried out if a ransom is not paid in bitcoin.
[src:ddos-mitigation-deep/denial-of-service-attack] Security experts recommend targeted websites to not pay the ransom.
[src:ddos-mitigation-deep/denial-of-service-attack] The attackers tend to get into an extended extortion scheme once they recognize that the target is ready to pay.
[src:ddos-mitigation-deep/denial-of-service-attack] First discovered in 2009, the HTTP slow POST attack sends a complete, legitimate HTTP POST header, which includes a *Content-Length* field to specify the size of the message body to follow.
[src:ddos-mitigation-deep/denial-of-service-attack] However, the attacker then proceeds to send the actual message body at an extremely slow rate (e.g.
[src:ddos-mitigation-deep/denial-of-service-attack] Due to the entire message being correct and complete, the target server will attempt to obey the *Content-Length* field in the header and wait for the entire body of the message to be transmitted, which can take a very long time.
[src:ddos-mitigation-deep/denial-of-service-attack] The attacker establishes hundreds or even thousands of such connections until all resources for incoming connections on the victim server are exhausted, making any further connections impossible until all data has been sent.
[src:ddos-mitigation-deep/denial-of-service-attack] It is notable that unlike many other DoS or DDoS attacks, which try to subdue the server by overloading its network or CPU, an HTTP slow POST attack targets the *logical* resources of the victim, which means the victim would still have enough network bandwidth and processing power to operate.
[src:ddos-mitigation-deep/denial-of-service-attack] Combined with the fact that the Apache HTTP Server will, by default, accept requests up to 2GB in size, this attack can be particularly powerful.
[src:ddos-mitigation-deep/denial-of-service-attack] HTTP slow POST attacks are difficult to differentiate from legitimate connections and are therefore able to bypass some protection systems.
[src:ddos-mitigation-deep/denial-of-service-attack] OWASP, an open source web application security project, released a tool to test the security of servers against this type of attack.
[src:ddos-mitigation-deep/denial-of-service-attack] A Challenge Collapsar (CC) attack is an attack where standard HTTP requests are sent to a targeted web server frequently.
[src:ddos-mitigation-deep/denial-of-service-attack] The Uniform Resource Identifiers (URIs) in the requests require complicated time-consuming algorithms or database operations which may exhaust the resources of the targeted web server.
[src:ddos-mitigation-deep/denial-of-service-attack] In 2004, a Chinese hacker nicknamed KiKi invented a hacking tool to send these kinds of requests to attack a NSFOCUS firewall named Collapsar, and thus the hacking tool was known as Challenge Collapsar, or *CC* for short.
[src:ddos-mitigation-deep/denial-of-service-attack] Consequently, this type of attack got the name *CC attack*.
[src:ddos-mitigation-deep/denial-of-service-attack] A smurf attack relies on misconfigured network devices that allow packets to be sent to all computer hosts on a particular network via the broadcast address of the network, rather than a specific machine.
[src:ddos-mitigation-deep/denial-of-service-attack] The attacker will send large numbers of IP packets with the source address faked to appear to be the address of the victim.
[src:ddos-mitigation-deep/denial-of-service-attack] Most devices on a network will, by default, respond to this by sending a reply to the source IP address.
[src:ddos-mitigation-deep/denial-of-service-attack] If the number of machines on the network that receive and respond to these packets is very large, the victim's computer will be flooded with traffic.
[src:ddos-mitigation-deep/denial-of-service-attack] This overloads the victim's computer and can even make it unusable during such an attack.
[src:ddos-mitigation-deep/denial-of-service-attack] Ping flood is based on sending the victim an overwhelming number of ping packets, usually using the *ping* command from Unix-like hosts.
[src:ddos-mitigation-deep/denial-of-service-attack] It is very simple to launch, the primary requirement being access to greater bandwidth than the victim.
[src:ddos-mitigation-deep/denial-of-service-attack] Ping of death is based on sending the victim a malformed ping packet, which will lead to a system crash on a vulnerable system.
[src:ddos-mitigation-deep/denial-of-service-attack] The BlackNurse attack is an example of an attack taking advantage of the required Destination Port Unreachable ICMP packets.
[src:ddos-mitigation-deep/denial-of-service-attack] A specific example of a nuke attack that gained some prominence is the WinNuke, which exploited the vulnerability in the NetBIOS handler in Windows 95.
[src:ddos-mitigation-deep/denial-of-service-attack] A string of out-of-band data was sent to TCP port 139 of the victim's machine, causing it to lock up and display a Blue Screen of Death.
[src:ddos-mitigation-deep/denial-of-service-attack] Attackers have found a way to exploit a number of bugs in peer-to-peer servers to initiate DDoS attacks.
[src:ddos-mitigation-deep/denial-of-service-attack] The most aggressive of these peer-to-peer-DDoS attacks exploits the DC++ file sharing network.
[src:ddos-mitigation-deep/denial-of-service-attack] With peer-to-peer attacks there is no botnet and the attacker does not have to communicate with the clients it subverts.
[src:ddos-mitigation-deep/denial-of-service-attack] Instead, the attacker acts as a *puppet master*, instructing clients of large peer-to-peer file sharing hubs to disconnect from their peer-to-peer network and to connect to the victim's website instead.
[src:ddos-mitigation-deep/denial-of-service-attack] Permanent denial-of-service (PDoS), also known loosely as phlashing, is an attack that damages a system so badly that it requires replacement or reinstallation of hardware.
[src:ddos-mitigation-deep/denial-of-service-attack] Unlike the distributed denial-of-service attack, a PDoS attack exploits security flaws which allow remote administration on the management interfaces of the victim's hardware, such as routers, printers, or other networking hardware.
[src:ddos-mitigation-deep/denial-of-service-attack] The PDoS is a pure hardware-targeted attack that can be much faster and requires fewer resources than using a botnet in a DDoS attack.
[src:ddos-mitigation-deep/denial-of-service-attack] Because of these features, and the potential and high probability of security exploits on network-enabled embedded devices, this technique has come to the attention of numerous hacking communities.
[src:ddos-mitigation-deep/denial-of-service-attack] BrickerBot, a piece of malware that targeted IoT devices, used PDoS attacks to disable its targets.
[src:ddos-mitigation-deep/denial-of-service-attack] PhlashDance is a tool created by Rich Smith (an employee of Hewlett-Packard's Systems Security Lab) used to detect and demonstrate PDoS vulnerabilities at the 2008 EUSecWest Applied Security Conference in London, UK.
[src:ddos-mitigation-deep/denial-of-service-attack] A distributed denial-of-service attack may involve sending forged requests of some type to a very large number of computers that will reply to the requests.
[src:ddos-mitigation-deep/denial-of-service-attack] Using Internet Protocol address spoofing, the source address is set to that of the targeted victim, which means all the replies will go to (and flood) the target.
[src:ddos-mitigation-deep/denial-of-service-attack] This reflected attack form is sometimes called a distributed reflective denial-of-service (DRDoS) attack.
[src:ddos-mitigation-deep/denial-of-service-attack] ICMP echo request attacks (Smurf attacks) can be considered one form of reflected attack, as the flooding hosts send Echo Requests to the broadcast addresses of mis-configured networks, thereby enticing hosts to send Echo Reply packets to the victim.
[src:ddos-mitigation-deep/denial-of-service-attack] Some early DDoS programs implemented a distributed form of this attack.
[src:ddos-mitigation-deep/denial-of-service-attack] Amplification attacks are used to magnify the bandwidth that is sent to a victim.
[src:ddos-mitigation-deep/denial-of-service-attack] Many services can be exploited to act as reflectors, some harder to block than others.
[src:ddos-mitigation-deep/denial-of-service-attack] DNS amplification attacks involves an attacker sending a DNS name lookup request to one or more public DNS servers, spoofing the source IP address of the targeted victim.
[src:ddos-mitigation-deep/denial-of-service-attack] The attacker tries to request as much information as possible, thus amplifying the DNS response that is sent to the targeted victim.
[src:ddos-mitigation-deep/denial-of-service-attack] Since the size of the request is significantly smaller than the response, the attacker is easily able to increase the amount of traffic directed at the target.
[src:ddos-mitigation-deep/denial-of-service-attack] Simple Network Management Protocol (SNMP) and Network Time Protocol (NTP) can also be exploited as reflectors in an amplification attack.
[src:ddos-mitigation-deep/denial-of-service-attack] An example of an amplified DDoS attack through the NTP is through a command called monlist, which sends the details of the last 600 hosts that have requested the time from the NTP server back to the requester.
[src:ddos-mitigation-deep/denial-of-service-attack] A small request to this time server can be sent using a spoofed source IP address of some victim, which results in a response 556.9 times the size of the request being sent to the victim.
[src:ddos-mitigation-deep/denial-of-service-attack] This becomes amplified when using botnets that all send requests with the same spoofed IP source, which will result in a massive amount of data being sent back to the victim.
[src:ddos-mitigation-deep/denial-of-service-attack] It is very difficult to defend against these types of attacks because the response data is coming from legitimate servers.
[src:ddos-mitigation-deep/denial-of-service-attack] These attack requests are also sent through UDP, which does not require a connection to the server.
[src:ddos-mitigation-deep/denial-of-service-attack] This means that the source IP is not verified when a request is received by the server.
[src:ddos-mitigation-deep/denial-of-service-attack] To bring awareness of these vulnerabilities, campaigns have been started that are dedicated to finding amplification vectors which have led to people fixing their resolvers or having the resolvers shut down completely.
[src:ddos-mitigation-deep/denial-of-service-attack] The Mirai botnet works by using a computer worm to infect hundreds of thousands of IoT devices across the internet.
[src:ddos-mitigation-deep/denial-of-service-attack] The worm propagates through networks and systems taking control of poorly protected IoT devices such as thermostats, Wi-Fi-enabled clocks, and washing machines.
[src:ddos-mitigation-deep/denial-of-service-attack] The owner or user will usually have no immediate indication of when the device becomes infected.
[src:ddos-mitigation-deep/denial-of-service-attack] The IoT device itself is not the direct target of the attack; it is used as part of a larger attack.
[src:ddos-mitigation-deep/denial-of-service-attack] Once the hacker has enslaved the desired number of devices, they instruct the devices to try to contact an ISP.
[src:ddos-mitigation-deep/denial-of-service-attack] In October 2016, a Mirai botnet attacked Dyn which is the ISP for sites such as Twitter, Netflix, etc.
[src:ddos-mitigation-deep/denial-of-service-attack] As soon as this occurred, these websites were all unreachable for several hours.
[src:ddos-mitigation-deep/denial-of-service-attack] RUDY attack targets web applications by starvation of available sessions on the web server.
[src:ddos-mitigation-deep/denial-of-service-attack] Much like Slowloris, RUDY keeps sessions at a halt using never-ending POST transmissions and sending an arbitrarily large content-length header value.
[src:ddos-mitigation-deep/denial-of-service-attack] Manipulating maximum segment size and selective acknowledgement (SACK) may be used by a remote peer to cause a denial of service by an integer overflow in the Linux kernel, potentially causing a kernel panic.
[src:ddos-mitigation-deep/denial-of-service-attack] The shrew attack is a denial-of-service attack on the Transmission Control Protocol where the attacker employs man-in-the-middle techniques.
[src:ddos-mitigation-deep/denial-of-service-attack] It exploits a weakness in TCP's re-transmission timeout mechanism, using short synchronized bursts of traffic to disrupt TCP connections on the same link.
[src:ddos-mitigation-deep/denial-of-service-attack] A slow read attack sends legitimate application layer requests, but reads responses very slowly, keeping connections open longer hoping to exhaust the server's connection pool.
[src:ddos-mitigation-deep/denial-of-service-attack] The slow read is achieved by advertising a very small number for the TCP Receive Window size, and at the same time emptying clients' TCP receive buffer slowly, which causes a very low data flow rate.
[src:ddos-mitigation-deep/denial-of-service-attack] A sophisticated low-bandwidth DDoS attack is a form of DoS that uses less traffic and increases its effectiveness by aiming at a weak point in the victim's system design, i.e., the attacker sends traffic consisting of complicated requests to the system.
[src:ddos-mitigation-deep/denial-of-service-attack] Essentially, a sophisticated DDoS attack is lower in cost due to its use of less traffic, is smaller in size making it more difficult to identify, and it can hurt systems which are protected by flow control mechanisms.
[src:ddos-mitigation-deep/denial-of-service-attack] A SYN flood occurs when a host sends a flood of TCP/SYN packets, often with a forged sender address.
[src:ddos-mitigation-deep/denial-of-service-attack] Each of these packets is handled like a connection request, causing the server to spawn a half-open connection, send back a TCP/SYN-ACK packet, and wait for a packet in response from the sender address.
[src:ddos-mitigation-deep/denial-of-service-attack] However, because the sender's address is forged, the response never comes.
[src:ddos-mitigation-deep/denial-of-service-attack] These half-open connections exhaust the available connections the server can make, keeping it from responding to legitimate requests until after the attack ends.
[src:ddos-mitigation-deep/denial-of-service-attack] A **teardrop attack** involves sending mangled IP fragments with overlapping, oversized payloads to the target machine.
[src:ddos-mitigation-deep/denial-of-service-attack] This can crash various operating systems because of a bug in their TCP/IP fragmentation re-assembly code.
[src:ddos-mitigation-deep/denial-of-service-attack] Windows 3.1x, Windows 95 and Windows NT operating systems, as well as versions of Linux before versions 2.0.32 and 2.1.63 are vulnerable to this attack.
[src:ddos-mitigation-deep/denial-of-service-attack] One of the fields in an IP header is the *fragment offset* field, indicating the starting position, or offset, of the data contained in a fragmented packet relative to the data in the original packet.
[src:ddos-mitigation-deep/denial-of-service-attack] If the sum of the offset and size of one fragmented packet differs from that of the next fragmented packet, the packets overlap.
[src:ddos-mitigation-deep/denial-of-service-attack] When this happens, a server vulnerable to teardrop attacks is unable to reassemble the packets resulting in a denial-of-service condition.
[src:ddos-mitigation-deep/denial-of-service-attack] Voice over IP has made abusive origination of large numbers of telephone voice calls inexpensive and easily automated while permitting call origins to be misrepresented through caller ID spoofing.
[src:ddos-mitigation-deep/denial-of-service-attack] TDoS can exist even without Internet telephony.
[src:ddos-mitigation-deep/denial-of-service-attack] In the 2002 New Hampshire Senate election phone jamming scandal, telemarketers were used to flood political opponents with spurious calls to jam phone banks on election day.
[src:ddos-mitigation-deep/denial-of-service-attack] Widespread publication of a number can also flood it with enough calls to render it unusable, as happened by accident in 1981 with multiple +1-area code-867-5309 subscribers inundated by hundreds of calls daily in response to the song "867-5309/Jenny".
[src:ddos-mitigation-deep/denial-of-service-attack] TDoS differs from other telephone harassment (such as prank calls and obscene phone calls) by the number of calls originated.
[src:ddos-mitigation-deep/denial-of-service-attack] By occupying lines continuously with repeated automated calls, the victim is prevented from making or receiving both routine and emergency telephone calls.
[src:ddos-mitigation-deep/denial-of-service-attack] Related exploits include SMS flooding attacks and black fax or continuous fax transmission by using a loop of paper at the sender.
[src:ddos-mitigation-deep/denial-of-service-attack] It takes more router resources to drop a packet with a TTL value of 1 or less than it does to forward a packet with a higher TTL value.
[src:ddos-mitigation-deep/denial-of-service-attack] When a packet is dropped due to TTL expiry, the router CPU must generate and send an ICMP time exceeded response.
[src:ddos-mitigation-deep/denial-of-service-attack] Generating many of these responses can overload the router's CPU.
[src:ddos-mitigation-deep/denial-of-service-attack] A UPnP attack uses an existing vulnerability in Universal Plug and Play (UPnP) protocol to get past network security and flood a target's network and servers.
[src:ddos-mitigation-deep/denial-of-service-attack] The attack is based on a DNS amplification technique, but the attack mechanism is a UPnP router that forwards requests from one outer source to another.
[src:ddos-mitigation-deep/denial-of-service-attack] The UPnP router returns the data on an unexpected UDP port from a bogus IP address, making it harder to take simple action to shut down the traffic flood.
[src:ddos-mitigation-deep/denial-of-service-attack] According to the Imperva researchers, the most effective way to stop this attack is for companies to lock down UPnP routers.
[src:ddos-mitigation-deep/denial-of-service-attack] In 2014, it was discovered that Simple Service Discovery Protocol (SSDP) was being used in DDoS attacks known as an SSDP reflection attac*k* *with amplification*.
[src:ddos-mitigation-deep/denial-of-service-attack] Many devices, including some residential routers, have a vulnerability in the UPnP software that allows an attacker to get replies from UDP port 1900 to a destination address of their choice.
[src:ddos-mitigation-deep/denial-of-service-attack] With a botnet of thousands of devices, the attackers can generate sufficient packet rates and occupy bandwidth to saturate links, causing the denial of service.
[src:ddos-mitigation-deep/denial-of-service-attack] Because of this weakness, the network company Cloudflare has described SSDP as the "Stupidly Simple DDoS Protocol".
[src:ddos-mitigation-deep/denial-of-service-attack] Defensive responses to denial-of-service attacks typically involve the use of a combination of attack detection, traffic classification and response tools, aiming to block traffic the tools identify as illegitimate and allow traffic that they identify as legitimate.
[src:ddos-mitigation-deep/denial-of-service-attack] A list of response tools include the following.
[src:ddos-mitigation-deep/denial-of-service-attack] All traffic destined to the victim is diverted to pass through a *cleaning center* or a *scrubbing center* via various methods such as: changing the victim IP address in the DNS system, tunneling methods (GRE/VRF, MPLS, SDN), proxies, digital cross connects, or even direct circuits.
[src:ddos-mitigation-deep/denial-of-service-attack] The cleaning center separates *bad* traffic (DDoS and also other common internet attacks) and only passes good legitimate traffic to the victim server.
[src:ddos-mitigation-deep/denial-of-service-attack] The victim needs central connectivity to the Internet to use this kind of service unless they happen to be located within the same facility as the cleaning center.
[src:ddos-mitigation-deep/denial-of-service-attack] DDoS attacks can overwhelm any type of hardware firewall, and passing malicious traffic through large and mature networks becomes more and more effective and economically sustainable against DDoS.
[src:ddos-mitigation-deep/denial-of-service-attack] Application front-end hardware is intelligent hardware placed on the network before traffic reaches the servers.
[src:ddos-mitigation-deep/denial-of-service-attack] It can be used on networks in conjunction with routers and switches and as part of bandwidth management.
[src:ddos-mitigation-deep/denial-of-service-attack] Application front-end hardware analyzes data packets as they enter the network, and identifies and drops dangerous or suspicious flows.
[src:ddos-mitigation-deep/denial-of-service-attack] Approaches to detection of DDoS attacks against cloud-based applications may be based on an application layer analysis, indicating whether incoming bulk traffic is legitimate.
[src:ddos-mitigation-deep/denial-of-service-attack] These approaches mainly rely on an identified path of value inside the application and monitor the progress of requests on this path, through markers called *key completion indicators*.
[src:ddos-mitigation-deep/denial-of-service-attack] In essence, these techniques are statistical methods of assessing the behavior of incoming requests to detect if something unusual or abnormal is going on.
[src:ddos-mitigation-deep/denial-of-service-attack] An analogy is to a brick-and-mortar department store where customers spend, on average, a known percentage of their time on different activities such as picking up items and examining them, putting them back, filling a basket, waiting to pay, paying, and leaving.
[src:ddos-mitigation-deep/denial-of-service-attack] If a mob of customers arrived in the store and spent all their time picking up items and putting them back, but never made any purchases, this could be flagged as unusual behavior.
[src:ddos-mitigation-deep/denial-of-service-attack] With blackhole routing, all the traffic to the attacked DNS or IP address is sent to a *black hole* (null interface or a non-existent server).
[src:ddos-mitigation-deep/denial-of-service-attack] To be more efficient and avoid affecting network connectivity, it can be managed by the ISP.
[src:ddos-mitigation-deep/denial-of-service-attack] A DNS sinkhole routes traffic to a valid IP address which analyzes traffic and rejects bad packets.
[src:ddos-mitigation-deep/denial-of-service-attack] Sinkholing may not be efficient for severe attacks.
[src:ddos-mitigation-deep/denial-of-service-attack] Intrusion prevention systems (IPS) are effective if the attacks have signatures associated with them.
[src:ddos-mitigation-deep/denial-of-service-attack] However, the trend among attacks is to have legitimate content but bad intent.
[src:ddos-mitigation-deep/denial-of-service-attack] Intrusion-prevention systems that work on content recognition cannot block behavior-based DoS attacks.
[src:ddos-mitigation-deep/denial-of-service-attack] An ASIC based IPS may detect and block denial-of-service attacks because they have the processing power and the granularity to analyze the attacks and act like a circuit breaker in an automated way.
[src:ddos-mitigation-deep/denial-of-service-attack] More focused on the problem than IPS, a DoS defense system (DDS) can block connection-based DoS attacks and those with legitimate content but bad intent.
[src:ddos-mitigation-deep/denial-of-service-attack] A DDS can also address both protocol attacks (such as teardrop and ping of death) and rate-based attacks (such as ICMP floods and SYN floods).
[src:ddos-mitigation-deep/denial-of-service-attack] DDS has a purpose-built system that can easily identify and obstruct denial of service attacks at a greater speed than a software-based system.
[src:ddos-mitigation-deep/denial-of-service-attack] In the case of a simple attack, a firewall can be adjusted to deny all incoming traffic from the attackers, based on protocols, ports, or the originating IP addresses.
[src:ddos-mitigation-deep/denial-of-service-attack] More complex attacks will however be hard to block with simple rules: for example, if there is an ongoing attack on port 80 (web service), it is not possible to drop all incoming traffic on this port because doing so will prevent the server from receiving and serving legitimate traffic.
[src:ddos-mitigation-deep/denial-of-service-attack] Additionally, firewalls may be too deep in the network hierarchy, with routers being adversely affected before the traffic gets to the firewall.
[src:ddos-mitigation-deep/denial-of-service-attack] Also, many security tools still do not support IPv6 or may not be configured properly, so the firewalls may be bypassed during the attacks.
[src:ddos-mitigation-deep/denial-of-service-attack] Similar to switches, routers have some rate-limiting and ACL capabilities.
[src:ddos-mitigation-deep/denial-of-service-attack] Most routers can be easily overwhelmed under a DoS attack.
[src:ddos-mitigation-deep/denial-of-service-attack] Nokia SR-OS using FP4 or FP5 processors offers DDoS protection.
[src:ddos-mitigation-deep/denial-of-service-attack] Nokia SR-OS also uses big data analytics-based Nokia Deepfield Defender for DDoS protection.
[src:ddos-mitigation-deep/denial-of-service-attack] Cisco IOS has optional features that can reduce the impact of flooding.
[src:ddos-mitigation-deep/denial-of-service-attack] Most switches have some rate-limiting and ACL capability.
[src:ddos-mitigation-deep/denial-of-service-attack] Some switches provide automatic or system-wide rate limiting, traffic shaping, delayed binding (TCP splicing), deep packet inspection and bogon filtering (bogus IP filtering) to detect and remediate DoS attacks through automatic rate filtering and WAN Link failover and balancing.
[src:ddos-mitigation-deep/denial-of-service-attack] These schemes will work as long as the DoS attacks can be prevented by using them.
[src:ddos-mitigation-deep/denial-of-service-attack] For example, SYN flood can be prevented using delayed binding or TCP splicing.
[src:ddos-mitigation-deep/denial-of-service-attack] Similarly, content-based DoS may be prevented using deep packet inspection.
[src:ddos-mitigation-deep/denial-of-service-attack] Attacks using Martian packets can be prevented using bogon filtering.
[src:ddos-mitigation-deep/denial-of-service-attack] Automatic rate filtering can work as long as set rate thresholds have been set correctly.
[src:ddos-mitigation-deep/denial-of-service-attack] WAN-link failover will work as long as both links have a DoS prevention mechanism.
[src:ddos-mitigation-deep/denial-of-service-attack] Threats may be associated with specific TCP or UDP port numbers.
[src:ddos-mitigation-deep/denial-of-service-attack] Blocking these ports at the firewall can mitigate an attack.
[src:ddos-mitigation-deep/denial-of-service-attack] For example, in an SSDP reflection attack, the key mitigation is to block incoming UDP traffic on port 1900.
[src:ddos-mitigation-deep/denial-of-service-attack] Blocking specific Time to live (TTL) values based on the network path length can be a viable option for blocking spoofed attacks.
[src:ddos-mitigation-deep/denial-of-service-attack] An unintentional denial-of-service can occur when a system ends up denied, not due to a deliberate attack by a single individual or group of individuals, but simply due to a sudden enormous spike in popularity.
[src:ddos-mitigation-deep/denial-of-service-attack] This can happen when an extremely popular website posts a prominent link to a second, less well-prepared site, for example, as part of a news story.
[src:ddos-mitigation-deep/denial-of-service-attack] The result is that a significant proportion of the primary site's regular users – potentially hundreds of thousands of people – click that link in the space of a few hours, having the same effect on the target website as a DDoS attack.
[src:ddos-mitigation-deep/denial-of-service-attack] A VIPDoS is the same, but specifically when the link was posted by a celebrity.
[src:ddos-mitigation-deep/denial-of-service-attack] When Michael Jackson died in 2009, websites such as Google and Twitter slowed down or even crashed.
[src:ddos-mitigation-deep/denial-of-service-attack] Many sites' servers thought the requests were from a virus or spyware trying to cause a denial-of-service attack, warning users that their queries looked like "automated requests from a computer virus or spyware application".
[src:ddos-mitigation-deep/denial-of-service-attack] News sites and link sites – sites whose primary function is to provide links to interesting content elsewhere on the Internet – are most likely to cause this phenomenon.
[src:ddos-mitigation-deep/denial-of-service-attack] The canonical example is the Slashdot effect when receiving traffic from Slashdot.
[src:ddos-mitigation-deep/denial-of-service-attack] It is also known as "the Reddit hug of death" and "the Digg effect".
[src:ddos-mitigation-deep/denial-of-service-attack] Similar unintentional denial-of-service can also occur via other media, e.g. when a URL is mentioned on television.
[src:ddos-mitigation-deep/denial-of-service-attack] In March 2014, after Malaysia Airlines Flight 370 went missing, DigitalGlobe launched a crowdsourcing service on which users could help search for the missing jet in satellite images.
[src:ddos-mitigation-deep/denial-of-service-attack] The response overwhelmed the company's servers.
[src:ddos-mitigation-deep/denial-of-service-attack] An unintentional denial-of-service may also result from a prescheduled event created by the website itself, as was the case of the Census in Australia in 2016.
[src:ddos-mitigation-deep/denial-of-service-attack] Legal action has been taken in at least one such case.
[src:ddos-mitigation-deep/denial-of-service-attack] In 2006, Universal Tube & Rollform Equipment Corporation sued YouTube: massive numbers of would-be YouTube.com users accidentally typed the tube company's URL, utube.com.
[src:ddos-mitigation-deep/denial-of-service-attack] As a result, the tube company ended up having to spend large amounts of money on upgrading its bandwidth.
[src:ddos-mitigation-deep/denial-of-service-attack] Routers have also been known to create unintentional DoS attacks, as both D-Link and Netgear routers have overloaded NTP servers by flooding them without respecting the restrictions of client types or geographical limitations.
[src:ddos-mitigation-deep/denial-of-service-attack] In computer network security, backscatter is a side-effect of a spoofed denial-of-service attack.
[src:ddos-mitigation-deep/denial-of-service-attack] In this kind of attack, the attacker spoofs the source address in IP packets sent to the victim.
[src:ddos-mitigation-deep/denial-of-service-attack] In general, the victim machine cannot distinguish between the spoofed packets and legitimate packets, so the victim responds to the spoofed packets as it normally would.
[src:ddos-mitigation-deep/denial-of-service-attack] These response packets are known as backscatter.
[src:ddos-mitigation-deep/denial-of-service-attack] If the attacker is spoofing source addresses randomly, the backscatter response packets from the victim will be sent back to random destinations.
[src:ddos-mitigation-deep/denial-of-service-attack] This effect can be used by network telescopes as indirect evidence of such attacks.
[src:ddos-mitigation-deep/denial-of-service-attack] The term *backscatter analysis* refers to observing backscatter packets arriving at a statistically significant portion of the IP address space to determine the characteristics of DoS attacks and victims.
[src:ddos-mitigation-deep/denial-of-service-attack] Many jurisdictions have laws under which denial-of-service attacks are illegal.
[src:ddos-mitigation-deep/denial-of-service-attack] UNCTAD highlights that 156 countries, or 80% globally, have enacted cybercrime laws to combat its widespread impact.
[src:ddos-mitigation-deep/denial-of-service-attack] Adoption rates vary by region, with Europe at a 91% rate, and Africa at 72%.
[src:ddos-mitigation-deep/denial-of-service-attack] In the US, denial-of-service attacks may be considered a federal crime under the Computer Fraud and Abuse Act with penalties that include years of imprisonment.
[src:ddos-mitigation-deep/denial-of-service-attack] The Computer Crime and Intellectual Property Section of the US Department of Justice handles cases of DoS and DDoS.
[src:ddos-mitigation-deep/denial-of-service-attack] In one example, in July 2019, Austin Thompson, aka DerpTrolling, was sentenced to 27 months in prison and $95,000 in restitution by a federal court for conducting multiple DDoS attacks on major video gaming companies, disrupting their systems for hours to days.
[src:ddos-mitigation-deep/denial-of-service-attack] In European countries, committing criminal denial-of-service attacks may, as a minimum, lead to arrest.
[src:ddos-mitigation-deep/denial-of-service-attack] The United Kingdom is unusual in that it specifically outlawed denial-of-service attacks and set a maximum penalty of 10 years in prison with the Police and Justice Act 2006, which amended Section 3 of the Computer Misuse Act 1990.
[src:ddos-mitigation-deep/denial-of-service-attack] In January 2019, Europol announced that "actions are currently underway worldwide to track down the users" of Webstresser.org, a former DDoS marketplace that was shut down in April 2018 as part of Operation PowerOFF.
[src:ddos-mitigation-deep/denial-of-service-attack] Europol said UK police were conducting a number of "live operations" targeting over 250 users of Webstresser and other DDoS services.
[src:ddos-mitigation-deep/denial-of-service-attack] On January 7, 2013, Anonymous posted a petition on the whitehouse.gov site asking that DDoS be recognized as a legal form of protest similar to the Occupy movement, the claim being that the similarity in the purpose of both is same.
[src:ddos-mitigation-deep/rate-limiting] In computer networks, **rate limiting** is used to control the rate of requests sent or received by a network interface controller.
[src:ddos-mitigation-deep/rate-limiting] It can be used to prevent DoS attacks and limit web scraping.
[src:ddos-mitigation-deep/rate-limiting] Research indicates flooding rates for one zombie machine are in excess of 20 HTTP GET requests per second, legitimate rates much less.
[src:ddos-mitigation-deep/rate-limiting] Rate limiting should be used along with throttling pattern to minimize the number of throttling errors.
[src:ddos-mitigation-deep/rate-limiting] Hardware appliances can limit the rate of requests on layer 4 or 5 of the OSI model.
[src:ddos-mitigation-deep/rate-limiting] Rate limiting can be induced by the network protocol stack of the sender due to a received ECN-marked packet and also by the network scheduler of any router along the way.
[src:ddos-mitigation-deep/rate-limiting] While a hardware appliance can limit the rate for a given range of IP-addresses on layer 4, it risks blocking a network with many users which are masked by NAT with a single IP address of an ISP.
[src:ddos-mitigation-deep/rate-limiting] Deep packet inspection can be used to filter on the session layer but will effectively disarm encryption protocols like TLS and SSL between the appliance and the protocol server (i.e. web server).
[src:ddos-mitigation-deep/rate-limiting] Protocol servers using a request / response model, such as FTP servers or typically Web servers may use a central in-memory key-value database, like Redis or Aerospike, for session management.
[src:ddos-mitigation-deep/rate-limiting] A rate limiting algorithm is used to check if the user session (or IP address) has to be limited based on the information in the session cache.
[src:ddos-mitigation-deep/rate-limiting] In case a client made too many requests within a given time frame, HTTP servers can respond with status code 429: Too Many Requests.
[src:ddos-mitigation-deep/rate-limiting] However, in some cases (i.e. web servers) the session management and rate limiting algorithm should be built into the application (used for dynamic content) running on the web server, rather than the web server itself.
[src:ddos-mitigation-deep/rate-limiting] When a protocol server or a network device notice that the configured request limit is reached, then it will offload new requests and not respond to them.
[src:ddos-mitigation-deep/rate-limiting] Sometimes they may be added to a queue to be processed once the input rate reaches an acceptable level, but at peak times the request rate can even exceed the capacities of such queues and requests have to be thrown away.
[src:ddos-mitigation-deep/rate-limiting] Data centers widely use rate limiting to control the share of resources given to different tenants and applications according to their service level agreement.
[src:ddos-mitigation-deep/rate-limiting] A variety of rate limiting techniques are applied in data centers using software and hardware.
[src:ddos-mitigation-deep/rate-limiting] Virtualized data centers may also apply rate limiting at the hypervisor layer.
[src:ddos-mitigation-deep/rate-limiting] Two important performance metrics of rate limiters in data centers are resource footprint (memory and CPU usage) which determines scalability, and precision.
[src:ddos-mitigation-deep/rate-limiting] There usually exists a trade-off, that is, higher precision can be achieved by dedicating more resources to the rate limiters.
[src:ddos-mitigation-deep/rate-limiting] A considerable body of research with focus on improving performance of rate limiting in data centers.
